ops.insert: What did the Moscow Treaty on Strategic Offensive Reductions do?

textDelta: What did the Moscow Treaty on Strategic Offensive Reductions do? The Moscow Treaty on Strategic Offensive Reductions (MOST) was a treaty signed on December 12, 1991, between the Soviet Union and the United States. The treaty aimed to reduce the number of nuclear weapons in the world by up to 50%.

ops.insert: On a global scale, trends are suggesting that with rising incomes and urbanization we are seeing a rise in which food commodities?

textDelta: On a global scale, trends are suggesting that with rising incomes and urbanization we are seeing a rise in which food commodities? There is some evidence that food commodities are rising in prices around the world. For example, in the United States, the cost of wheat has increased by about 50% since 2007, while corn prices have increased by about 20%.

ops.insert: International trade will almost always benefit both countries, so why do countries try to protect their own firms from exposure to the world market?

textDelta: International trade will almost always benefit both countries, so why do countries try to protect their own firms from exposure to the world market? There are a few reasons why countries may try to protect their own firms from the world market. One reason is that it is in their own economic interest to do so. If their own firms are not able to compete with those from other countries, they may find it harder to achieve economic growth and be able to provide their citizens with the goods and services they need.
